<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-10-07T15:14:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-10-07T15:14:00-05:00" n="644" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d644">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">822.61334/139: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bading</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-10-07T15:00:00-05:14"><hi rend="italic">October 7,
                                        1924—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 8—9:30
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>15. Department’s telegram number 17, October 1, 4 p.m. Have had interview
                            with the President, and his answer submitted in writing absolutely
                            ignores promises; merely quotes law of 1921 and states he favors strict
                            compliance therewith.</p>
                        <p>Recommend immediate instructions by telegraph calling for the fulfillment
                            of promises without evasion.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bading</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>